  "text": "The key purpose of an autonomous drone is to lessen human input and error through the help of Machine Learning (ML) and Artificial Intelligence (AI) [8]. Carev, et al. [9], invented a universal metric to measure research programs, planning innovative programs, and comparing efforts to develop autonomous control technology. This metric is known as the Autonomous Control Level (ACL) for a UAV. The ACL metric system was made by Air Force Research Laboratory’s Air Vehicles Directorate. Most UAVs today which are operational commonly do not rank high on the ACL metric [10]. Fig. 2, shows the levels of autonomy and the trends followed according to ACL metrics. In this paper, the correlation between the varying regulations for UAVs around the world and their levels of autonomy are dis’Motors and cussed. It explores the definitions, functionalities, current research, and challenges of achieving ACL 10 UAVs. Section propellors’, offers a summary of the essential components of a UAV, including motors and propellers that facilitate flight and enable adaptation to different flight conditions. Section ’Flight control and ESC’ describes the data processing unit, flight controller, and electronic speed controller of the UAV. Section ’Vision and mapping’ discusses the importance of visual input for autonomy and surveys the most widely used technologies for mapping and visualizing environments. Section ’Communication’, covers the current communication layer in UAVs, emphasizing its importance in establishing tactical and strategic commands for groups of drones. Section ’Path planning’ focuses on path planning, including current methodologies for allowing drones to think for themselves and plan or reroute their trajectories. Section ’Simulation’ emphasizes the role of simulation in achieving a fully autonomous swarm, while Section ’Conclusion’ concludes the paper. ## **Motors and propellors** BLDC motors are essential in today’s mechanical applications. These motors are preferred because of their high-power efficiency and density. The power yield of BLDCs can be limited by varying the voltage applied to ESCs [11]. In accordance with the fundamental principles governing electric motors, the resultant mechanical power (P) is evaluated by considering M as the torque which is measured in Newton-meters (Nm), ω as the angular velocity which is expressed in radians per second (rad/s), and n as the rotational speed denoted in revolutions per minute (RPM) [12]. Propellers are coupled on top of these motors that provide lift to the aircraft by spinning and generating airflows which further accelerate mass in one direction, counteracting the force of",
